## 2. Core Game Loop

### 2.1 The Proximity Bond

When two players with Caravan installed are within BLE range (~10m) for at least 30 seconds, their caravans begin linking. Chain strength is measured in seconds of proximity. Leaving range pauses the counter; returning resumes it. Bonds decay at 50% per 48 real-world hours without renewal.

### 2.2 Chain Building

Chains extend through the social graph: A chains to B, B chains to C — the bonus pool grows with each link. Chains can extend indefinitely but bonuses are tuned for realistic groups of 2–8. A chain of strangers on a commuter train, a protest, a crowded market — these are the naturally emergent structures the game rewards.

> No GPS is used at any point. The entire world of Caravan is defined by BLE proximity alone. Physical movement is the only map.

### 2.3 The Caravan

Each player owns a Caravan — a post-apocalyptic survivor group with:

- **Survivors** — named characters with roles: Scout, Medic, Engineer, Cook, Guard
- **Resources** — Food, Water, Fuel, Scrap, Medicine, and currency holdings
- **A Camp** — upgradeable base that stores resources and buffs survivors
- **A Level** — player progression 1–99. Always hardcore. Death resets to 1.
- **Reputation or Infamy** — persistent through death. The social record of who you are.

### 2.4 Time & Decay

Time passes at a 10:1 ratio. Survivors consume resources daily. The game is designed so active urban commuters sustain a healthy caravan without grinding — the pressure is gentle but persistent, and isolation is always the slow death.

