## 4. Entity Types

Every entity in Caravan is a real BLE device. No server-spawned world. Three types are distinguished by app state, player opt-in flags, and behaviour signals.

### 4.1 Hostile Mobs

> *Raiders are players who have opted into Raider Mode, or server-seeded bots ensuring danger exists even in sparse areas.*

Raider Mode is an opt-in toggle. When active, a player's caravan is flagged hostile to all nearby non-chained players. Raiders earn bonus loot multipliers and access to the Raider economy — black market goods unavailable to civilians. In return, they accumulate Infamy (see Section 11).

| Tier | Encounter Signal | Threat Profile |
|---|---|---|
| Scavenger | 1–2 nearby hostiles | Low HP, fast. Drops basic resources. Targets isolated low-levels. |
| Raider Band | 3–5 nearby hostiles | Coordinated. Targets mid-level players. Drops equipment and currency. |
| Warlord Crew | 6+ nearby hostiles | Rare. Extremely dangerous. Guards high-tier loot. Attacks organised chains. |
| Server Bot | No nearby players | AI-simulated. Weaker than real Raiders. Ensures the game is never empty. |

Combat resolves asynchronously. When a hostile enters proximity, a raid event begins — a 2-minute commitment window opens, both parties secretly allocate fighters and equipment, and the outcome resolves at timer expiry. Neither player needs to be actively watching.

### 4.2 Neutral Players

> *Neutrals have not opted into any faction. They will not attack unprovoked but will defend if raided.*

Neutral players appear as unknown silhouettes in the proximity feed. Behaviour reveals intent: a neutral who stays in range 5+ minutes without initiating is likely a commuter. One who ping-pongs in and out is likely probing defences.

### 4.3 Friendly NPC Traders

> *Traders are server-seeded bots and players in Merchant Mode. They do not attack and cannot be attacked by civilians. Raiders who attack Merchants suffer a Market Reputation penalty.*

Traders broadcast a recognisable BLE signal pattern visible in the proximity UI. When a Trader enters range, their wares appear in the market screen. Prices are set by the Trader (bot) or the player in Merchant Mode. All Trader transactions settle immediately.

