## 5. Combat System

### 5.1 Raid Resolution

- Both parties see a 2-minute commitment window when a raid begins
- Each party secretly allocates Fighters (survivors) and Equipment (consumables)
- Active chain members in proximity apply a defensive bonus to the defender
- At timer expiry, outcome resolves based on committed power plus 10–15% random variance
- Survivors can be injured (temporary) or killed (permanent) based on margin of defeat

### 5.2 Defensive Instakill — Level Gap Mechanic

> **This bonus fires ONLY when a higher-level player initiates an attack against a lower-level player. It cannot be used offensively. A lower-level player who initiates an attack receives no instakill bonus.**

When a higher-level player attacks a lower-level player, the defender gains a defensive instakill chance:

```
instakill_chance = (level_gap / 98)^2 * 35%    [defender only — never on offence]
```

This scales quadratically — negligible for small gaps, significant for large ones. At maximum gap (level 99 attacking level 1), the defender has a ~35% chance of an outright kill, resetting the attacker to level 1 and dropping their full loot. The mechanic functions as a natural deterrent against predatory targeting of new players, without a hard rule or lockout.

| Gap | Instakill Chance | Attacker Risk Profile |
|---|---|---|
| < 20 levels | < 5% | Negligible. Near-fair combat, normal risk. |
| 20–45 levels | 5–21% | Meaningful. Attacker should consider their exposure. |
| 45–70 levels | 21–30% | High. Attacker is gambling significant progression. |
| 70–98 levels | 30–35% | Severe. Attacking a near-new player is likely unprofitable. |

### 5.3 Hardcore Mode — Always On

> *There is no softcore mode. There never will be. Death is the central dramatic engine of the game's economy.*

When a player's last survivor is killed:

- Player level resets to 1
- All equipped items and held resources drop as a loot bundle in the BLE context of death
- Reputation and Infamy scores are fully preserved — social standing survives death
- Open market orders are cancelled; escrowed assets enter the loot pool
- Camp structures and upgrades are preserved — your base survives
- Survivor names and history are memorialised in the Lost Caravan log
- A 10-minute protection window activates — cannot be raided immediately

A level 99 player dying to a coordinated Raider gang and dropping legendary gear into the world is the story Caravan is built to tell. High-level player deaths are the economy's primary liquidity events.

