## 6. Loot System

### 6.1 Loot Drops

When a player dies or a raid is won decisively, loot drops as a timed chest broadcast over BLE. The chest is tied to the BLE context of death — not a GPS location.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Drop Broadcast | Chest signal broadcasts to all devices within ~15m BLE range at moment of drop |
| Killer Priority | Killing player (or their chain) has a 60-second exclusive claim window |
| Open Window | After 60 seconds, any nearby player can claim the chest |
| Chain Share | Chain members share the exclusive window — first-come first-served within it |
| Chest Decay | Unclaimed chests expire after 10 minutes; resources partially recycle to economy |

> *The loot is there. Someone nearby will get it. Your chain-mates might grab it first. This is intentional. Combat is a gamble, not a guarantee.*

### 6.2 Loot Tiers

| Tier | Source | Contents |
|---|---|---|
| Common | Scavenger kills, Trader remnants | Basic resources: Food, Water, Scrap, small currency |
| Uncommon | Raider Band kills, PvP victories | Equipment: weapons, armour, survivor skill books |
| Rare | Warlord Crew kills, high-level PvP | Named Equipment: items with unique modifiers |
| Legendary | Level 80–99 player deaths | Full equipment sets, rare blueprints, large currency |

### 6.3 Bound Items

Legendary items become Bound on equip — untradeable until their carrier dies. Bound items can only re-enter the economy through death, ensuring legendary gear remains scarce and its movement through the world is always a consequence of violence.

