## 7. Currency System

> *Caravan operates a multi-currency economy. There is no single universal medium of exchange. Nations set their own monetary policy, syndicates run parallel shadow ledgers, and the exchange rates between them are live market signals.*

### 7.1 Tier 1 — Sovereign Currency (Valuables)

Valuables is the primary in-game currency denomination. Each nation issues its own named variant, and the backing mechanism is determined by that nation's elected leader:

| Backing Method | Description |
|---|---|
| Commodity-pegged | Currency is redeemable for a fixed quantity of a specific resource. Stable under normal conditions; vulnerable to embargos targeting that commodity. |
| Free-floating | Value determined entirely by market confidence and supply/demand. Flexible but susceptible to bank runs and coordinated sell pressure. |
| Mixed reserve | Nation holds a basket of commodities and Cipher reserves as backing. More resilient; requires active treasury management. |
| Undeclared | Leader has not published backing method. High uncertainty premium — players discount the currency in exchange. |

Nations tax transactions denominated in their currency. Tax rates are set by the elected leader and apply to all market orders settled in that nation's Valuables. Tax revenue flows to the national treasury, which the leader can spend on public bonuses, infrastructure, or military responses.

### 7.2 Tier 2 — Commodity Receipts

Any player holding a physical resource can issue commodity receipts — tradeable notes redeemable for a specific quantity of that resource. Receipts are:

- Tradeable on the global market order book
- Priced by the market independently of Valuables
- Redeemable only when the issuing player is within BLE range of the redeemer
- Subject to counterparty risk — if the issuer dies before redemption, the receipt is worthless

The counterparty risk on receipts creates a natural credit market. High-reputation players issue receipts that trade at face value. Unknown players find their receipts discounted. This is emergent creditworthiness — no explicit credit score system is needed.

### 7.3 Tier 3 — Cipher (Syndicate Encrypted Scrip)

> **Cipher is not cryptocurrency. It is a closed in-game ledger system — a tamper-evident private transaction record maintained by the game server on behalf of a syndicate. No real-world value. No external wallet. No withdrawal.**

When a syndicate is founded or joined, its leader gains access to a private ledger — Cipher. Cipher functions as an alternative medium of exchange within and between syndicates:

| Property | Detail |
|---|---|
| Issuance | Only the syndicate leader can mint new Cipher. Minting is rate-limited to prevent inflation abuse. |
| Visibility | Only the syndicate leader sees the full transaction ledger. Members see their own balance and direct transactions only. |
| Verification | All transactions are cryptographically signed by the game server — tamper-evident, non-repudiable. |
| Anonymity | Transaction counterparties are visible only to the leader. Outsiders — including political authorities — cannot see Cipher flows. |
| Interoperability | Each syndicate runs its own Cipher. Two syndicates can establish a Cipher Bridge at a negotiated exchange rate. |
| Scope | Cipher is accepted wherever the syndicate has reach — primarily black market traders and Raider-aligned merchants. |

### 7.4 Cipher Bridge — Syndicate Alliances

A Cipher Bridge is a bilateral agreement between two syndicates to exchange their respective Cipher at a fixed or floating rate. Bridges are:

- Negotiated directly between syndicate leaders
- Published to both syndicates' members as a live exchange rate
- Revocable by either leader at any time — revocation is a hostile act
- The primary financial instrument of syndicate diplomacy

Two syndicates with an active Cipher Bridge have a financial incentive to avoid direct conflict — disrupting the bridge destroys the exchange value held by both memberships. This creates emergent peace agreements backed by economic self-interest rather than rule enforcement.

### 7.5 Exchange Rates

Exchange rates between all currency types — Valuables variants, commodity receipts, and Cipher — are set by the global market's order book. Any player can place orders to exchange one currency for another. The 5% auto-match rule applies to all currency exchange orders.

The Cipher/Valuables exchange rate is a live legitimacy signal. When Cipher trades at a premium to a nation's Valuables, it indicates market distrust of that nation's monetary policy. A widening spread is an early warning of political instability.

