## 8. Market System

### 8.1 Order Book

All tradeable assets — resources, equipment, commodity receipts, currency pairs — are traded on a single global order book. The order book combines real player orders with agent-model liquidity from the economic simulation.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Buy Order | Player specifies asset and max price. Funds escrowed immediately. |
| Sell Order | Player specifies asset and min price. Asset escrowed immediately. |
| 5% Match Rule | Orders auto-fill when buy and sell prices are within 5% of each other. |
| Settlement | Both parties receive their assets. Each pays/receives their stated price. No house spread. |
| No Partial Fills | Orders are all-or-nothing per quantity unit. Stack orders for large volumes. |
| Death Cancels | Player death cancels all open orders. Escrowed assets enter the loot pool. |
| Order Cap | Maximum 20 open orders per player simultaneously. |

### 8.2 Derivatives

| Instrument | Description |
|---|---|
| Futures | Contract to buy or sell a fixed quantity of a resource at a fixed price on a future in-game date. Used to hedge against supply disruption from embargos or raids. |
| Options | Right but not obligation to buy (call) or sell (put) a resource at a strike price before expiry. Premium paid upfront. Useful for speculating on political decisions. |
| Spreads | Simultaneous buy and sell of futures at different dates — captures the price difference between near and far delivery. Standard arbitrage instrument. |

Derivatives are priced by the agent simulation and player orders. A nation leader announcing an embargo on Fuel makes Fuel call options immediately valuable — players who positioned in advance profit significantly. This creates genuine information value around political decisions and syndicate intelligence.

### 8.3 Market Reputation

Players accumulate a Market Reputation score separate from combat Reputation or Infamy. Market Reputation is damaged by:

- Defaulting on commodity receipt redemptions
- Raiders attacking Merchant-mode players
- Manipulative order placement (detected by agent sim as wash trading patterns)

Low Market Reputation results in orders being deprioritised in matching queues and higher counterparty risk discounts applied to commodity receipts the player issues.

