## 12. Political System

### 12.1 Nations

A nation is not a geographic construct — there is no GPS. A nation is defined as a network of players who have declared allegiance to the same political entity. Nations form organically from high-density chain clusters. The boundaries are social, not spatial.

### 12.2 Elections

Any player meeting the Reputation threshold can stand for election. Elections are held on a fixed real-time cycle (proposed: 30 real days per term). Voting is open to all nation members above a minimum activity threshold. A player with high Infamy cannot run for office — the records are public.

### 12.3 Leader Powers

| Power | Effect |
|---|---|
| Embargo | Prohibits import or export of a named commodity to/from a named nation. Commodity prices rise in the embargoed market; commodity-backed currencies face inflation pressure. |
| Tariff | Tax on trades involving a named commodity or foreign currency. Revenue goes to national treasury. Raises effective price for foreign buyers. |
| Tax rate | Set the transaction tax rate on all Valuables-denominated trades within the nation. Too high drives players to Cipher; too low depletes the treasury. |
| Treasury spend | Deploy treasury Valuables as public bonuses: chain bonus multipliers, camp upgrade subsidies, survivor recruitment drives. |
| Declare sanctions | Formal hostile designation against a syndicate — increases costs for players trading in that syndicate's Cipher within the nation. |
| Currency policy | Change or declare the nation's backing mechanism for Valuables. Undeclared policy incurs a market uncertainty discount. |

### 12.4 Losing Office

A nation leader loses office by:

- Term expiry and electoral defeat
- Currency collapse — if the nation's Valuables exchange rate falls below a critical threshold, a snap election is triggered automatically
- Reputation collapse — if the leader's Reputation score falls (e.g. they begin attacking players), they are immediately disqualified and a new election is called

