## 13. Syndicate System

### 13.1 NPC Syndicates

NPC syndicates are permanent world fixtures — ancient powers predating any player. Their leaders never change. They have fixed trading patterns, established Cipher networks, and historical relationships with specific commodities. They are the furniture of the wasteland economy that all players navigate around.

NPC syndicates provide the baseline black market liquidity that new players encounter. They do not pursue political power directly but respond to embargos and sanctions with predictable economic countermeasures.

### 13.2 Player Syndicates

Player syndicates rise and fall with their founders' Infamy. A syndicate exists as long as its leader maintains sufficient Infamy to command loyalty and control Cipher supply. If the leader dies at a critical moment, the syndicate's Cipher loses confidence — members may defect to NPC syndicates or rival player factions.

### 13.3 Syndicate Powers

| Power | Effect |
|---|---|
| Cipher minting | Issue new Cipher (rate-limited). Fund operations, pay members, build reserves. |
| Cipher Bridge | Establish bilateral exchange rate agreement with another syndicate. |
| Black market access | Control which goods flow through the black market and at what premium over the official exchange. |
| Bounties | Place Cipher bounties on named players — paid to whoever kills the target and delivers proof. |
| Protection rackets | Offer Merchant-mode players protection from Raiders in exchange for Cipher tribute. |
| Turf | Declare a BLE network cluster as syndicate territory — non-members pay a Cipher toll or face raiding. |

### 13.4 Political-Syndicate Tension

The core geopolitical dynamic: a nation leader can embargo a syndicate's key commodity, cutting its supply lines and driving up black market prices. The syndicate can respond by flooding the market with Valuables held in reserve, destabilising the nation's exchange rate. Neither side can directly destroy the other — they fight through market forces and proxy players.

A well-coordinated multi-syndicate attack — triggered by an overreaching embargo — can cause a full currency collapse, ending the leader's term. This is the most sophisticated play in the game, requiring intelligence, coordination, and patience.

