## 14. Currency Destabilisation

> *Full currency collapse is possible. It requires coordinated multi-syndicate action and represents the most consequential event in the game's political economy.*

### 14.1 Destabilisation Mechanics

| Mechanism | Effect |
|---|---|
| Embargo inflation | Cutting a commodity-backed currency's peg commodity drives inflation. Players holding that currency lose purchasing power. Sell pressure accelerates. |
| Cipher flood | Syndicate dumps large Valuables reserves onto the market via anonymous Cipher transactions. Sudden supply shock. Exchange rate falls. |
| Bank run | Mass order cancellation and conversion to competing currencies or commodity receipts. Self-reinforcing: each exit makes remaining holders more anxious. |
| Receipt default | If a major commodity receipt issuer dies or defaults, confidence in all receipts from that nation falls. Credit contraction. |
| Tariff war | Two nations imposing retaliatory tariffs raises prices across the board, reducing real purchasing power of both currencies. |

### 14.2 Collapse Outcome

When a nation's Valuables exchange rate falls below the collapse threshold:

- Snap election triggered — sitting leader immediately loses office
- Nation reverts to barter or may voluntarily adopt a stronger nation's Valuables
- Treasury holdings are distributed to nation members proportionally
- All outstanding Valuables-denominated futures contracts settle at collapse price
- Recovery requires a new elected leader to declare and sustain a new monetary policy

Collapse is recoverable. A nation that collapses and rebuilds with a credible backing mechanism can regain market confidence. The political narrative of recovery — and the opportunistic players who bought the collapsed currency at the bottom — is part of the game's intended story.

